  "prompt": "What's the difference between scattering and diffraction?",
  "response": "Scattering and diffraction are two different physical phenomena involving the interaction of waves with materials or obstacles.\n\n**Scattering:**\n- Scattering involves the deflection of waves (such as light, sound, or particles) when they encounter obstacles or irregularities in a medium.\n- It can occur in various forms, such as Rayleigh scattering, Mie scattering, or Bragg scattering, depending on the size of the scatterers and the wavelength of the waves.\n- Scattering can be elastic (where the wave's frequency remains unchanged) or inelastic (where the wave's frequency changes).\n- It results in the dispersion of waves in various directions.\n- Scattering is what we observe when light is diffused in the atmosphere, causing phenomena like the blue sky or red sunsets.\n\n**Diffraction:**\n- Diffraction is the bending or spreading of waves when they encounter an obstacle or slit that is comparable in size to the wavelength of the waves.\n- It is governed by the principles of wave interference and is more pronounced when the slit or obstacle is small relative to the wavelength.\n- Diffraction leads to the formation of patterns, such as fringes or rings, due to constructive and destructive interference.\n- It is commonly observed in experiments involving light passing through slits or around edges, such as in the famous double-slit experiment.\n- Diffraction is essential in many applications, including the design of optical instruments and the study of wave behavior in physics.\n\nIn summary, scattering involves waves interacting with irregularities and being redirected, while diffraction involves waves bending around obstacles and creating interference patterns. Both phenomena are essential to understanding and describing wave behavior in different contexts.",
